e Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe newly revised edition of The Social Studies Curriculum presents the definitive overview of the primary issues facing teachers creating learning experiences for students in social studies. The book connects the diverse elements of the social studies curriculum—global education, social issues-centered education, and the roles of history, and the arts and sciences—thereby offering a unique and contemporary perspective, one that separates it from other texts used in today's social studies classrooms. Thoroughly updated, this edition includes new material on the use of literature in social studies classrooms, inclusive education, citizenship education, and the impact of standards and high stakes testing on social studies curriculum and pedagogy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCurriculum planningxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aCurriculum planningzUnited States. 0aSocial sciencesxStudy and teaching (Elementary)xCurriculaxUnited States. 0aSocial sciencesxStudy and teaching (Elementary)xCurriculazUnited States. 0aSocial sciencesxStudy and teaching (Secondary)xCurriculaxUnited States. 0aSocial sciencesxStudy and teaching (Secondary)xCurriculazUnited States. 4aEducation : Curriculum. 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh1 aBernard-Powers, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpstein, Terrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Ronald W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleury, Stephen C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Rich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHursh, David W., eco